[0.030, "o", "\u001b[?25l\b\u001b[m\u000f \u001b[6;27He, generally called php.ini, is responsible\u001b[7;25He aspects of PHP's be\u001b[9;10Hempts to find and load this configuration from a numbe\u001b[10;5He following is a summary of its search orde\u001b[11;16He spe\u001b[12;8He PHPRC environment variable\u001b[13;12Her of predefined registry ke\u001b[14;10Hent working directory (exce\u001b[15;8He web server's directory (for SAPI modules), or dire\u001b[16;7Herwise\u001b[17;8He directory from the --with-config-file-path compile time option, or the\u001b[18;14He\u001b[19;4Hee the PHP docs for more spe\u001b[20;16Het/configuration.file\u001b[22;5He syntax of the file is extremely simple.  Whitespace and line\u001b[23;4Heginning with a semicolon are silently ignored (as you probably guesse\u001b[24;4Hection headers (e.g. [Foo]) are also silently ignored, eve\u001b[25;5Hey might mean something in the future\u001b[27;6Hectives following the section heading [PATH=/www/mysite\u001b[28;19Hes in the /www/mysite directory.  Directive\u001b[29;15He section heading [HOST=www.example\u001b[30;10Hes served from www.example.com.  Directives set in these\u001b[31;5Hecial sections cannot be overridden by user-defined INI file\u001b[32;12He. Currently, [PATH=] and [HOST=] sections only work unde\u001b[34;16Het/ini.se\u001b[36;6Hectives are specified using the\u001b[37;6Hective = value\u001b[38;6Hective names are *case sensitive* - foo=bar is differe\u001b[39;6Hectives are variables used to configure PHP or PHP exte\u001b[40;5Here is no name validation.  If PHP can't find an expecte\u001b[41;6Hective because it is not set or is mistyped, a default value will be use\u001b[43;5He value can be a string, a number, a PHP constant (e.g. E_ALL or M_PI), one\u001b[44;8He INI constants (On, Off, True, False, Yes, No and None) or an expre\u001b[45;4He.g. E_ALL & ~E_NOTICE), a quoted string (\"bar\"), or a reference\u001b[46;5Heviously set variable or directive (e\u001b[47;153H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f1,1 \u001b[48;2H\u001b[?25h"]
